text: Luis de Quixano y Font served as Mayor of Ponce, Puerto Rico from 1863 to 1865 and is renowned for constructing the Plaza del Mercado de Ponce, a 65-kiosk farmers' market modeled after the Paris farmers' market, which occupies an entire city block.

In the 1936 college football season, Marquette University's team, the Golden Avalanche, was coached by Frank Murray and played as an independent team at Marquette Stadium in Milwaukee, Wisconsin. They ended the season with a 7-2 record, losing to TCU in the first Cotton Bowl Classic.
Victorville's KVTR is a commercial radio station that broadcasts ranchera music under the name "Victor 1590 AM" to the Victor Valley area on 1590 AM.

The Paulinerkirche was a church in Leipzig that was originally built in 1231 as the Klosterkirche St. Pauli for the Dominican monastery. It became the university church after the foundation of the University of Leipzig in 1409 and was later donated to the university after the Protestant Reformation. Johann Sebastian Bach served as director of music for holiday services in the church from 1723-25. The church was destroyed in 1968 during the communist regime of East Germany but a new building, the Paulinum, was built on the site beginning in 2007 to resemble the former church.
Moskovia Airlines, located in Zhukovsky, Moscow, Russia, provided both domestic and international passenger and cargo charters, with its primary hub at Domodedovo Airport.
The James B. Garrison Bridge consists of two car bridges that cross the Pee Dee River/Lake Tillery, connecting Stanly and Montgomery Counties and accommodating NC 24/NC 27/NC 73.
O-Games released Hysteria Hospital: Emergency Ward, a simulation/strategy game similar to Diner Dash, on June 16, 2009 in North America.
The Rees River in New Zealand flows into upper Lake Wakatipu in the South Island and is named after William Gilbert Rees, the founder of Queenstown.

The 1987-88 FA Cup is the 107th season of the oldest football knockout competition, with many lower league clubs competing in preliminary and qualifying rounds before the 28 winners advanced to the First Round Proper.
The main-belt asteroid 1249 Rutherfordia was discovered on November 4, 1932, by K. Reinmuth at Heidelberg and named after the city Rutherford in New York.

Germany's inaugural airfield, the Johannisthal Air Field, was established on September 26, 1909, just a few weeks after the world's first airfield in Rheims, France. It is situated 15 km (9.3 mi) South-East of Berlin, between Johannisthal and Adlershof.

The Chatham Stakes is a Group 3 Thoroughbred horse race held annually during the VRC Spring Racing Carnival at Flemington Racecourse in Melbourne, Australia. It is an open handicap race over 1400 metres and was previously known as the Guvera Stakes in 2015. The total prize money for the race is A$200,000 and there is a trophy worth $1,500.
The Turkish State Hydraulic Works supported the construction of Kaymaz Dam in Turkey.
WC and the Maad Circle's second album, Curb Servin', was released after an eleven-year hiatus from 1996 to 2007. It reached #85 on the Billboard 200 and #15 on the Top R&B/Hip-hop albums chart.
The Swallow's Nest Cave is located in Gibraltar, a British Overseas Territory.

FNB Field is a baseball park in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, USA, located on City Island, in the Susquehanna River. It is the home field of the Harrisburg Senators AA minor league baseball team of the Washington Nationals, as well as the Harrisburg City Islanders soccer club of the USL. The ballpark has a capacity of 6,187 people and underwent a $45 million renovation that began in 2008.
The Predator, a wooden roller coaster, was constructed by Dinn Corporation and designed by Curtis D. Summers in 1990 at Darien Lake.

The estuarine perch, also known as sea pikeperch or sea zander, is a type of fish in the Percidae family. It can be found in several countries including Azerbaijan, Bulgaria, Iran, Kazakhstan, Moldova, Romania, Russia, Turkmenistan, and Ukraine.

Aya Nakahara is a manga artist from Osaka who won the 49th Shogakukan Manga Award for her shōjo manga, Lovely Complex, which tells the story of a tall high school girl who falls in love with a short guy.
Loudon introduced the Field Elm variety Ulmus minor 'Concavaefolia' in 1838 in Arboretum et Fruticetum Britannicum.
The top futsal championship in San Marino, founded in 2006, is currently made up of 12 teams and is organized by the Federazione Sammarinese Giuoco Calcio.
The ATP Tulsa, a men's tennis tournament, took place in Tulsa, Oklahoma from 1978-1980 as part of the ATP Tour, and was played on indoor hard courts.

The Marshalsea in Dublin was a debtor's prison located on Bridgefoot St. It was named after a prison in Southwark and was considered the worst prison in the city after the closure of The Black Dog prison. It was run for profit and families of prisoners could live there for protection. In 1802, a new prison was deemed necessary due to its ruinous state. Robert Emmet used it as an arsenal in 1803 and the Dublin Militia used it as a barracks in the later 19th century. It was demolished in 1975 and some of the stone was used to repair the City wall at Cook Street.

The Farmer's Wife was a women's magazine published in St. Paul, Minnesota from 1897 to 1939. It provided advice on farming, housekeeping, cooking, and published fiction, with over a million subscribers at its peak. The magazine was established by Webb Publishing Company, which became one of the largest agricultural publishers in the US. It was later sold to Farm Journal in 1939 and continued to be published until 1970.

DD Urdu is a government-owned TV channel based in Delhi that aims to promote the Urdu language among Indian citizens. Its headquarters are located near Mandi House metro station in New Delhi, and it is available for broadcasting in India, parts of Asia, China, and Gulf Countries.
Established in 1963, Rangunia College is a private college located in Rangunia Upazila, Chittagong, Bangladesh and is the second college to be established in the country after Chittagong College.

MUH is a private teaching hospital located on the campus of Macquarie University in Australia. It integrates clinical care, education, and research and is the first private hospital on a university campus in the country. The hospital has 182 beds, 12 operating theatres, and over 200 medical specialists. It also has a modern imaging center and radiation oncology unit. Construction costs for the hospital were over $380 million.
The 1926 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final was the final game of the 1926 tournament, which featured the best Gaelic football teams in Ireland.

The Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball team of 1922-1923 was coached by Walter Meanwell, who had been with the team for nine seasons. They played their home games at the Red Gym in Madison, Wisconsin and were part of the Big Ten Conference.

On June 1, 2013, Bayern Munich won the 2012-13 DFB-Pokal tournament by defeating VfB Stuttgart 3-2 at the Olympiastadion in Berlin. This victory, along with previous wins in the Champions League and Bundesliga, allowed Munich to achieve a continental treble, a feat that had only been accomplished by six other European teams and had never been achieved by a German team before.

Eutelsat 16C, previously known as SESAT 1, is a satellite operated by Eutelsat that offers telecommunications and broadcasting services across a vast area from the Atlantic Ocean to Eastern Russia, including Siberia. It also provides broadcasting services to Africa through steerable spotbeams. In 2010, it took over some services from the W2 satellite.

Derby Silk Mill, previously called Derby Industrial Museum, is a museum showcasing industry and history in Derby, England. It is located in Lombe's Mill, a historic silk mill at the southern end of the Derwent Valley Mills World Heritage Site.
Rafaël Antonio Porras Acevedo, a retired Colombian cyclist, was born in Sogamoso in 1954.

Niels Kristian Trochmann Iversen, born in Denmark in 1982, is a successful international motorcycle speedway rider who contributed to Denmark's victories in the Speedway World Cup in 2006, 2008, 2012, and 2014.
The 136th Krazy Kat cartoon, Port Whines, is an animated short film produced by Columbia Pictures Corporation.

Strait Area Transit is a non-profit cooperative charity that provides public transportation in Inverness County and Richmond County, Nova Scotia, Canada. It offers fixed route and Dial-A-Ride services on a daily basis in the South-Central Inverness County, Richmond County area.
The 13th race of the 1978 Formula One season was the Dutch Grand Prix held on August 27th at Zandvoort.
The Archdiocese of Mansa is a subordinate diocese located in the city of Mansa, Zambia, within the ecclesiastical province of Kasama.
NGC 7314 is a small, active spiral galaxy in Piscis Austrinus that can be observed as a fuzzy object in a 6-inch telescope despite its photographic magnitude of 11.6.
The Appleton Stakes is a Grade III horse race for horses aged four and above, held annually in March at Gulfstream Park in Hallandale Beach, Florida, and raced on turf over a distance of one mile.
Shayade Hug won the title of Miss Earth Switzerland 2014 and will participate in Miss Earth 2014.

MoreArt is an annual public art event held along the Upfield Bike Path, railway corridor, and Sydney Road in the City of Moreland. The event, which began in 2010, features artworks and sculptures that can be accessed by bicycle, train, or on foot. The event encourages artists to use disused public spaces and invites the community to discover and appreciate the Moreland area. The event is supported by the City of Moreland and has been praised for increasing vibrancy and social cohesion in the community.
(308193) 2005 CB79 is a likely fragment from dwarf planet Haumea, with a diameter of 158 km and no known companion, according to observations by Mike Brown in 2012.
CDF is a Chilean sports pay TV channel that launched in 2003 and is owned by the Chilean football league.

The lake is a popular spot for various activities like skiing, biking, and hiking during winter and spring. Skiers should be careful near Portage Glacier as the glacier's movement can break up thick ice and create unstable patches even in midwinter. The mid-spring season of "crust skiing" is highly valued by skiers.

Marlin is a magazine, both in print and digital form, that focuses on big game fishing worldwide. It is published by the Bonnier Corporation and based in Winter Park, Florida. The editor-in-chief is John Brownlee, and the magazine provides information on billfishing destinations, live-baiting and trolling techniques, influential people in the sport, and equipment reviews.
The 18th TIFF was held in Toronto, Canada from September 9-18, 1993. M. Butterfly was the opening film and Strapped won Forest Whitaker the FIPRESCI International Critics' Award.
In 2007, minor characters were introduced in Hollyoaks, and this is a list of them in chronological order.

The 4th Moscow International Film Festival took place from July 5 to 20, 1965. The top prize was awarded to both the Soviet film War and Peace, directed by Sergei Bondarchuk, and the Hungarian film Twenty Hours, directed by Zoltán Fábri.
The fourth installment of the Looney Tunes series, The Booze Hangs High, was released in 1930 and stars Bosko, the first cartoon character created by Warner Bros.

The Hempstead Branch is an electrified rail line owned and operated by the Long Island Rail Road in New York. It starts at Queens Interlocking and runs parallel to the Main Line, splitting southward at Floral Park and continuing east to Hempstead Crossing. The line stops at Hollis and Queens Village stations on the Main Line, but these stations are not served by any other Main Line branch. The line is double tracked until Garden City Station, where it becomes a single track for the final 1.4 miles to Hempstead station.
Kawaii Kon is a Honolulu-based convention that focuses on Japanese animation and comics.

The Břeclav city ice rink in the Czech Republic is mainly used for ice hockey and is home to HC Břeclav. It has a capacity of 4200 and was constructed in 1972. Additionally, it frequently hosts the Ivan Hlinka Memorial Tournament.
The Oak Ridge Boys released their studio album Common Thread on May 24, 2005.
Fulvio Pierangelini's Gambero Rosso restaurant in San Vincenzo, Tuscany, was ranked 12th in the world by Restaurant Top 50 2008 and received 2 Michelin stars before closing in November 2008.

Charter Communications owns News 13, an American cable news channel that offers 24-hour news coverage centered on Central Florida, including Brevard, Flagler, Lake, Marion, Orange, Osceola, Seminole, Sumter, and Volusia counties.

Hot Doug's was a popular Chicago restaurant that specialized in hot dogs and sausages. It closed in 2014 after being in its second location in the Avondale neighborhood. The restaurant was known for its unique menu and affordable gourmet food, and its head chef, Doug Sohn, was well-regarded. Despite long lines, it was a popular destination for both locals and tourists.

The New Formalist was a literary periodical published electronically monthly and in print once a year, featuring leading formal poets in English. It was edited by Leo Yankevich and distributed by The New Formalist Press. The magazine stopped publishing in 2010 but also produced The New Formalist E-book Series.
The Ottoman Empire's Western Army had a corps called the Scutari Corps, also known as the Işkodra Corps or Shkoder Corps, which was created in the Scutari region during the First Balkan War.
On December 22, 1775, a small battle occurred in what is now Greenville County, South Carolina, during the American Revolutionary War, known as the Battle of Great Cane Brake.
The Old National Bank Events Plaza in Evansville, Indiana hosts EvilleCon, a three-day anime convention held every March.
Playboy Brazil is a franchise of the magazine founded in 1975 by Editora Abril, making it the fourth international version after Germany, Italy, and France.
The UMK is a university in Toruń, Poland, named after Nicolaus Copernicus, who was born in the town in 1473.

Tranmere Rovers Football Club, a professional football club located in Birkenhead, Wirral, played their 84th season in the Football League during the 2010-11 season, which was the 110th season of competitive association football.
Epiales, also known as Epialos, Epioles, or Epialtes, was the daemon and embodiment of nightmares in Greek Mythology, also referred to as melas oneiros or Black Dream.

Kuben, or the Arena Polarica, is an indoor ice hockey arena located in Haparanda, Sweden. It was established in 1990 and can accommodate up to 1500 viewers. Asplöven HC of the HockeyAllsvenskan uses it as their home arena.

Kite is a town in Johnson County, Georgia, USA, named after Shaderick Kight who donated the land for its construction. The town has a population of 241 and is located along the Little Ohoopee River. It is part of the Dublin Micropolitan Statistical Area.
WMU is a prominent university in Wenzhou, Zhejiang, overseen by the Zhejiang Provincial Government.

The Galaxy is a horse race held in Sydney, Australia in March or April. It is a Group One Thoroughbred open handicap race that covers a distance of 1100 metres at Rosehill Gardens Racecourse. The total prize money for the race is A$700,000.
The Bradford County Airport, which is owned by the Bradford County Airport Authority, is a public airport located two miles south of Towanda, Pennsylvania.
Thor: Son of Asgard is an iOS game that follows the Marvel Comics version of Thor, with comic book-style cutscenes. The character's appearance and personality are based on the movie version.

Ultra Bali is an outdoor electronic music festival for those 19 and over, held at the Potato Head Beach Club in Bali, Indonesia. It is part of Ultra Music Festival's expansion to twenty countries and took place in September 2015 and 2016.
Tuam Golf Club is a parkland course situated in Tuam, County Galway and has been a member of the Golfing Union of Ireland since 1940, having been established in 1904.
The International Grand Prix Losail was a single-day cycling race in Qatar that was part of the UCI Asia Tour's 1.2 category, and it was only held once.
The Narvik Arctic Eagles are a Norwegian ice hockey team that competes in the second tier of the sport, known as the First Division.

The 1977 season was the Kansas City Chiefs' worst until 2008, with only two wins out of fourteen games. Head coach Paul Wiggin was fired after a 44-7 loss to Cleveland in week seven, and Tom Bettis served as interim head coach for the remainder of the season. The team ended the season with a six-game losing streak and a 2-12 record.
The 21st season of the Yugoslav Cup, the top football knockout competition in SFR Yugoslavia, took place in 1967-68. It is also known as the "Marshal Tito Cup" since its establishment in 1946.
In Lawrence County, Ohio, there are fourteen townships, including Symmes Township, which had a population of 470 according to the 2000 census.

Château Neercanne is a Michelin-starred restaurant in Maastricht, Netherlands, with a current head chef named Hans Snijders. It was awarded one or two Michelin stars from 1957-1982 and 1986-present, and received 16.0 points out of 20 from GaultMillau in 2013. Previous head chefs include Theo Koch and Ber Stassen.
The Challenge Tour hosted the Moroccan Golf Classic every year from 2002 to 2010, except for 2007.

Les Disques du Crépuscule is a Belgian independent record label established in 1980 by Michel Duval and Annik Honoré. It has a sublabel called Factory Benelux, and both are currently managed by James Nice, a former employee. The label's catalogue numbers are typically prefixed by the letters TWI, which stands for "twilight."

The Diocese of Iran is part of the Anglican Province of Jerusalem and the Middle East, established in 1912 as the Diocese of Persia. It became part of the Jerusalem Archbishopric in 1957 and is currently led by Bishop Azad Marshall, titled Bishop in Iran.

The Musée national Gustave Moreau in Paris is an art museum showcasing the works of Symbolist painter Gustave Moreau. It was originally his home, which he transformed into a studio and museum in 1895. The museum now houses his drawings, paintings, watercolors, and sculptures.
The TNDCLU is a construction workers' trade union in Tamil Nadu, India, affiliated with the All India Central Council of Trade Unions, aiming to expand its membership to 15,000 in 2005.
The Crown Point Light on Lake Champlain was transformed from a regular lighthouse into a tribute to Samuel de Champlain's exploration of the lake.
Tipperary won the 1995 All-Ireland Under-21 Hurling Championship final against Kilkenny at Semple Stadium, Thurles on 10 September 1995.

The Irish Builder was a prosperous trade journal in Dublin, Ireland, with various names, including The Dublin Builder and Irish Builder and Technical Journal. J.J. Lyons, an architect, was its initial owner and editor.

i-D is a UK magazine that focuses on fashion, music, art, and youth culture. It was created by Terry Jones, a designer and former Vogue art director, in 1980. The magazine started as a hand-stapled fanzine with typewriter text and has since become a glossy publication while still maintaining its focus on street style and youth culture. i-D has also organized exhibitions globally and released multiple books.
The Russian Federal Space Agency used Progress M-03M, also known as Progress 35P, to supply the International Space Station.

McChord Field is a US Air Force base in Pierce County, Washington, home to the 62d Airlift Wing and focused on worldwide strategic airlift. It was consolidated with Fort Lewis in 2010 to create Joint Base Lewis-McChord, a cost-saving measure to improve war fighting capability and efficiency.
The 59th Woody Woodpecker cartoon, Helter Shelter, was created by Walter Lantz Productions and distributed by Universal International on January 17, 1955.

Canutillo Stadium, owned and operated by the Canutillo Independent School District, opened in 2005 and has a capacity of 12,000. Located 14 miles from downtown El Paso, it is home to the Canutillo Eagles and primarily used for high school football and soccer games. The stadium used to be home to the Indios USA and in 2008, visitor bleachers were added to hold approximately 3,000 people. In 2011, a new blue turf was added.

Puthuyugam TV is a Tamil entertainment channel based in Chennai, owned by the SRM Group of Companies and run by The New Generation Media Corporation. It features various shows including Malli, Kayitham, and Nayanmargal, among others, and is a sister channel to Puthiya Thalaimurai TV.
The Giant Cave in Gibraltar is owned by John.
The Hamilton Spectator is a daily newspaper, except on Sundays, that was established in 1846 and is based in Hamilton, Ontario, Canada.

The 1997 Afro-Asian Club Championship was the 10th competition between the winners of the African Champions' Cup and the Asian Club Championship. Pohang Steel and Zamalek played in a two-legged final, with Zamalek winning on away goals and becoming the only club to win the Championship twice.
Oxigar Belenos is a Spanish rugby team located in Avilés.
The Hokkaido Soccer League is a non-professional football league in Hokkaido, Japan.

The 168 Film Project is a Christian film festival where participants are given a random scripture verse based on a theme to create a short film within 168 hours. Over 750 short films have been produced for the competition worldwide from 2003 to 2012.

Meta Linhas Aéreas, previously known as META - Mesquita Transportes Aéreos, was a Brazilian airline that provided domestic and international flights to northern Brazil, Guyana, and Suriname. It was based in Boa Vista and operated from Boa Vista-Atlas Brasil Cantanhede International Airport. However, it stopped operating scheduled flights in July 2011.

Francisco Bravo Medical Magnet High School is a Los Angeles Unified School District magnet high school that caters to students interested in healthcare. It is situated in the Boyle Heights neighborhood of Los Angeles, California, near the LAC+USC Medical Center.

Relentless Records, led by co-founder Shabs Jobanputra, gained recognition for hit singles like "Re-Rewind" and "Girls Like This" and has released albums by artists such as Joss Stone, KT Tunstall, So Solid Crew, and Cage the Elephant.

The Taradale Viaduct is a large wrought iron bridge over Back Creek in Victoria, Australia, built between 1858 and 1861 as part of the Melbourne, Mount Alexander and Murray River Railway. The bridge was designed by Captain Andrew Clarke and completed by Bryson and O'Hara, with ironwork made by Rowland Brotherhood under the supervision of Isambard Kingdom Brunel. The bridge was strengthened with steel trestles in the 1930s to accommodate heavier locomotives. It is listed on the Victorian Heritage Register and the National Trust Register.

The Church of the Good Shepherd in Kensington, Philadelphia was an Episcopal congregation founded in 1868. It merged with Emmanuel Church in 1994 to form the Church of Emmanuel and the Good Shepherd. The building, designed by T. Frank Miller and located at 2121-2127 East Cumberland Street, was demolished in 2016. The church was a reminder of the mid to late 19th century English immigrant experience in Kensington and Philadelphia, which is often referred to as a hidden and forgotten group. However, they built unique neighborhoods, cultural institutions, and worship sites.
Valley Transit provides public transportation in Walla Walla County, Washington, with 10 routes serving Walla Walla and College Place.
This is a list of albums by the Japanese noise band Hijōkaidan.

The Diocese of Guildford is a Church of England diocese that includes nine districts in Surrey, parts of north-east Hampshire, and a parish in Greater London. It is under the Province of Canterbury and is led by the Bishop of Guildford with Guildford Cathedral as its main church.

Before the 1992-93 season, S.S. Lazio underwent significant changes, including the acquisition of Paul Gascoigne and the purchase of the club by Sergio Cragnotti. Giuseppe Signori, a left-wing player, was placed as a striker and scored 26 goals in Serie A, preventing the team from finishing lower than fifth place.

Alloa Athletic returned to the Scottish Second Division in the 2012-13 season after being promoted from the Scottish Third Division in the previous season. They participated in the Challenge Cup, Scottish League Cup, and Scottish Cup.
Hitomi Kudo is a former AV idol and Japanese actress who is also known as Hitomi Kudou or Hitomi Kudoh. Her Chinese name is Gung1 Tang4 Tung4 in Cantonese Yale.
Roy Rosenzweig founded the CHNM at George Mason University in 1994 to explore the use of digital media and information technology in historical research, education, preservation, and outreach.

Mexico won the 2013 U-19 Northern Ireland Youth Soccer Tournament, which is an international football competition held annually on the north coast of Northern Ireland and includes three sections for U19, U17, and U15.
The Derrinstown Stud 1,000 Guineas Trial is a flat horse race for three-year-old thoroughbred fillies in Ireland. It takes place in May at Leopardstown and covers a distance of 1 mile (1,609 metres).

Chard Museum, located in Chard, Somerset, England, is a small museum that opened in 1970. It is housed in a converted 16th century listed building and features exhibits about local history and notable residents.
The Yangon Central Women's Hospital is a public hospital in Myanmar that serves as a teaching hospital for several universities.
The Coastal Range newt is a type of California newt found only in California, from Mendocino County to San Diego County.

Octavia is a Roman tragedy about Nero divorcing and exiling his wife Claudia Octavia and marrying Poppaea Sabina. The play also explores Nero's temper and disregard for Seneca's advice. Although once attributed to Seneca, modern scholarship suggests it was written after both Nero and Seneca's deaths during the Flavian period.

The Savages, a garage rock band from Bermuda, were active in the mid-1960s and are known for their album Live 'n Wild. The album, recorded live and featuring mostly original songs, is considered a seminal work in the genre and includes the classic anthem of youthful defiance, "The World Ain't Round It's Square."

The 2014 FFA Cup preliminaries were state-based knockout contests that served as a qualification route for the Australian association football knockout cup competition. Most clubs entered through their state federations, competing in a state-based cup tournament to advance to the Round of 32. 22 teams will qualify from these competitions, joining the 10 A-League clubs in the Round of 32.

The Iradier Arena, or Plaza de Toros de Vitoria-Gasteiz, is a bullring and arena in Vitoria-Gasteiz, Spain that opened in 1941. It has a capacity of 10,714 and is used for bullfighting and basketball, and was the temporary home of Saski Baskonia.

The Spirit of Bosnia is a quarterly literary magazine that focuses on the history, politics, and literature of Bosnia and Herzegovina. It publishes both fiction and non-fiction and was founded in 2006. Keith Doubt is the current editor-in-chief, and Omer Hadžiselimović was co-editor from 2006-2011.
Melaka United's 2016 season marks their 93rd in club history and their return to the Malaysia Premier League after being relegated in the 2010 season.
Natanz Steel Plant is a company town located in Karkas Rural District, Isfahan Province, Iran, with a population of 5 people in 4 families according to the 2006 census.
The Grand Teton Mall, which opened in 1984 in Idaho Falls, Idaho, features Dillard's, JCPenney, Sears, Macy's, Old Navy, Barnes & Noble, and a post office.
Jambojet is a budget airline based in Nairobi, Kenya, that began operating in 2014 and is owned by Kenya Airways.

The Diocese of York is a Church of England administrative division led by the Archbishop of York and covering the city of York, eastern North Yorkshire, and most of the East Riding of Yorkshire. It is divided into three archdeaconries and its cathedral is York Minster. It used to be larger, covering parts of several other counties.

Comic-Con Russia is an annual exhibition and fan convention for various forms of entertainment, including computer and video games, TV series, and comic movies. It was first held in 2014 alongside the IgroMir conference and has since expanded to include a wide range of pop culture and entertainment genres such as horror, animation, anime, manga, toys, collectible card games, video games, webcomics, and fantasy novels. The convention is organized by the committee of the Russian Game Developers Conference and Bubble Comics.
The Sidney Municipal Airport, also known as Lloyd W. Carr Field, is located three miles south of Sidney in Cheyenne County, Nebraska and is owned by the Sidney Airport Authority.
The Wisconsin State Fair is a yearly event that occurs in August for 11 days at the Wisconsin State Fair Park in West Allis, a Milwaukee suburb.
The Archdiocese of Białystok is situated in Białystok, Poland, and has a majority of Roman Catholic residents, but only a minority are active members.

The 2010 NFL playoffs began on January 8, 2011 and ended with the Green Bay Packers winning Super Bowl XLV on February 6. The new postseason overtime rules were in effect, but none of the games went into overtime. The rules state that if the team that wins the coin toss only scores a field goal on their first possession, the other team gets a possession. If the coin toss loser scores a touchdown, they win. If the score is tied, sudden death occurs. The Seattle Seahawks won their division with a 7-9 record, making it the second post-season in NFL history to include a team with a losing record.
Reunion Records, a Christian music label, was established in 1982 by Dan Harrell and Mike Blanton and is now part of the Provident Label Group, located in Brentwood, Tennessee, U.S.

The 1944 Alabama Crimson Tide football team, coached by Frank Thomas, played their home games at Denny Stadium, Legion Field, and the Cramton Bowl. They finished the season with a record of 5-2-2 and lost to Duke in the Sugar Bowl. The team was composed of players who were too young or physically unable to enlist in the military due to World War II, and were referred to as the "War Babies" by Coach Thomas.
Sky Greenland, previously known as Greenland Express, is a virtual airline based in Kangerlussuaq, Greenland. It began operating in June 2014 with only one leased Fokker 100 from Denim Air ACMI.
James Dunlop discovered NGC 1792, a spiral galaxy in the Columba constellation, on October 4, 1826.

In 2011, the Johnstown Generals had their debut season in the UIFL, finishing with a 6-8 record and missing the playoffs. They started the season by choosing Victor Seasy as their first pick in the draft.
The Valspar Championship is an annual men's professional golf tournament on the PGA Tour, held at the Copperhead Course in Palm Harbor, Florida.

Unionville Vineyard is a winery located in the Unionville area of East Amwell Township, Hunterdon County, New Jersey. It was established in 1988 and opened to the public in 1993. The vineyard spans 54 acres and produces 8,500 cases of wine annually. It is named after a former village in the vicinity.

The Chu-Han Contention was a power struggle between Western Chu, led by Xiang Yu, and Han, led by Liu Bang, for control of China after the collapse of the Qin dynasty in 206 BC. The war ended in 202 BC with Han emerging as the victor and Liu Bang becoming the first emperor of the Han dynasty.

In March 2013, 460 French soldiers participated in operation Doro 3, divided into two sub-groups and supported by engineers, artillery, and airmobile units. They harassed jihadists in the vicinity of Goram, using armored vehicles, artillery trucks, and helicopters. The French General Staff reported 15 Islamists neutralized, 8 pickups destroyed, and weapons and ammunition seized during raids in two villages. On March 17-18, explosions were heard north of Gao, and French reconnaissance destroyed 4 tubes of 122mm rocket launch.
Emmy the Great, also known as Emma-Lee Moss, released her debut album First Love on February 9, 2009 under Close Harbour Records, an independent label in the UK.

BZL/VGBR is a domestic airport in Barisal, Bangladesh. GMG Airlines, Royal Bengal Airlines, and United Airways used to fly to Dhaka from this airport. Biman Bangladesh Airlines resumed weekly flights in April 2015 after a nine-year hiatus.

Small Heath FC finished 7th in the 1904-05 Football League season, despite being in 3rd place with 8 matches remaining. They also lost in the first round of the FA Cup to Portsmouth, but won the Birmingham Senior Cup. The club considered changing their name to Birmingham City FC, but the shareholders were not in favor. The Coventry Road ground was overcrowded during a match with Aston Villa, prompting the directors to plan for a new home as the landlords would not sell the freehold or allow expansion.
Maidstone Borough Council (MBC) is the local authority for Maidstone Borough in Kent, UK.

Denbigh Golf Club is located in Denbighshire, Wales and offers an 18 hole parkland course with mature trees. Non-members can play on their "Pay and Play" course. In 2009, a father and son achieved a hole-in-one, with odds of 13,000-1. In 2013, the club appointed its first female president after 105 years of male presidents.
The Marimari River is a tributary of the Abacaxis River in the Amazonas state of north-western Brazil, and it joins the Abacaxis River just before it flows into the Paraná Urariá.

In the 1971 college football season, the University of Colorado at Boulder's football team, the Buffaloes, scored 370 points and allowed 220 points. They were coached by Eddie Crowder and participated in the Astro-Bluebonnet Bowl.
The Supreme Court of the United States made a significant antitrust ruling in Broadcast Music v. Columbia Broadcasting System, 441 U.S. 1 (1979).
The Winter Sports Complex in Ashgabat, Turkmenistan is a versatile indoor arena and one of the biggest ice hockey arenas in the CIS.
The 1981 Toledo Rockets football team won the MAC championship with a 9-3 record and defeated San Jose State in the California Bowl. Key players included Jim Kelso, Arnold Smiley, and Rodney Achter.
The highest futsal league in Bosnia and Herzegovina is called the Premier Futsal League and is overseen by the Football Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

Established in 2000, SMOD is a Malian band consisting of Sam, Mouzy, Ousco, and Donsky. The band's name is an acronym of their first names. Their music is a blend of rap, hip hop, folk, and traditional music. Mouzy left the band to pursue a solo career in France. Additionally, Smod is a popular term of endearment.
In their first season in 1932, the Boston Braves had four wins, four losses, and two ties, and placed fourth in the National Football League.
Mokulele Airlines is a US commuter airline located in Kona, Hawaii, that offers scheduled inter-island and charter flights to smaller airports in Hawaii.
We the Women is a popular weekly women's magazine published in Helsinki, Finland, written in Finnish.

Autopilot Off is a punk rock band from Orange County, NY consisting of Chris Hughes, Chris Johnson, Phil Robinson, and Rob Kucharek. In May 2011, a Facebook page was created with the band's name and "TwoThousandEleven" image, sparking rumors of a reunion. Autopilot Off confirmed they were working on new material on June 20 via their official Facebook page.

The football stadium in Belfast, Northern Ireland, known as the National Football Stadium at Windsor Park, serves as the home ground for Linfield F.C. and the Northern Ireland national football team, and hosts the finals of the Irish Cup and the Irish League Cup.

The Lincoln Handicap is a horse race in Great Britain for horses aged four years or older, run over a distance of 1 mile at Doncaster in late March or early April. It is the main event on the first Saturday of the turf flat racing season and is part of the Spring Double with the Grand National. David Dick is the only jockey to have won both races in 1956.
Kilkenny won the 2003 All-Ireland Under-21 Hurling Championship final against Galway at Semple Stadium, Thurles on 21 September 2003.

ESMoA is an art laboratory in El Segundo, California that aims to promote creativity through visual arts education and display. It offers three unique Experiences per year that showcase various media, including sculpture, painting, works on paper, performances, and photography. ESMoA's focus is on art education for students, families, and adults, and admission is free. The organization is run by Artlab21 Foundation, a non-profit public charity.
At the 1920 Summer Olympics, 48 sprinters from 22 nations competed in the men's 200 metres event held on August 19 and 20.

Punta Stilo is a headland in Calabria, Italy, located north of Monasterace and forming the western coast of the Gulf of Squillace. Pliny the Elder called it Cocynthum, while the names Punta Stilo and Stilida were first mentioned in the Itinerarium maritimum in the late fifth century AD.
Santa Clara participated in the Primeira Liga during the 2001-02 Portuguese football season.
The Pondo dwarf chameleon, also called the Transkei dwarf chameleon, is a chameleon found only in South Africa's Eastern Cape Province.
Sydney FC's 2014-15 season marked their 10th year in the A-League and their debut in the FFA Cup.

Saravah, established by Pierre Barouh in 1965, is a French record label that has featured artists such as Brigitte Fontaine, Areski Belkacem, Jacques Higelin, Pierre Akendengué, and Jean-Roger Caussimon.
East Sutton Park is a prison for women and young offenders in Kent, England, managed by the Prison Service.
Tess Arbez, an Irish alpine ski racer born in 1997, participated in the giant slalom event at the 2015 World Championships held in Beaver Creek, USA.
Raimmandhoo is a Meemu Atoll island with residents.
City Evangelical Church is an autonomous evangelical church located in Leeds, West Yorkshire, England, and is associated with the Fellowship of Independent Evangelical Churches.
The Ak-Chin Regional Airport, formerly known as Phoenix Regional Airport, is a privately owned public-use airport situated in Pinal County, Arizona, 28 nm southeast of Phoenix's CBD.

The Word is an instrumental/sacred steel/gospel blues jam band consisting of Robert Randolph, John Medeski, Luther Dickinson, Cody Dickinson, and Chris Chew. They formed due to a shared love of gospel music and the Sacred Steel tradition. The band is unique in that they have no vocals, and Medeski's organ and electric piano content is more experimental than traditional sacred steel music. The band's debut self-titled album was released in 2001 and includes a mixture of traditional gospel songs and original instrumentals. The group has toured and performed at various festivals, including Bonnaroo and Conan.

Deer Island Prison, situated on Deer Island in Boston Harbor, Massachusetts, operated from 1880 to 1991. It was also called the Deer Island House of Industry and later, House of Correction. The prison housed individuals convicted of various crimes, including drunkenness, drug possession, disorderly conduct, and larceny, with relatively short-term sentences. At the time of its closure, around 1,500 inmates were held at Deer Island.

Sadra is a vocal genre in Hindustani classical music and is considered the oldest form in that tradition. A composition set to the 10-beat Jhap tala is called a Sadra and exists in the tala metres of tivra (7 beats), sul (10 beats), and chau (12 beats).

Kaatyayani Channel is a 24/7 Hindu TV channel in Hindi owned by Veecon Group. It is accessible on major cable, DTH platforms, and online, including live streaming on YouTube and the website www.kaatayayanimata.com.

Power Engineering is a monthly magazine for power engineering and generation professionals in North America, published by PennWell Corporation. It covers new developments in power plant design, construction, and operation. PennWell also publishes Power Engineering International, which covers the rest of the world.

James Mackey dropped out of a pre-med program at the University of Missouri to become a professional poker player. He won a World Series of Poker bracelet at the age of 21, defeating experienced players in a short final table. Mackey started playing poker online with a $75 investment and turned it into $20,000, leading him to pursue poker professionally. He finished as the runner-up in the 2008 World Championship Mixed Event, earning almost $300,000.
The Catholic Diocese of the Faroe Islands was active until the Protestant Reformation, and the Faroe Islands are now part of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Copenhagen.
Aluminij is in their second season in the Slovenian PrvaLiga, the top division in Slovenia, and they participate in both the Slovenian PrvaLiga and the Slovenian Football Cup.
The NCTL is a Thai trade union federation that is associated with the International Trade Union Confederation.

The balsam fir, also known as Abies balsamea, is a type of fir tree that is found in eastern and central Canada, as well as the northeastern United States. It can be found in areas ranging from Newfoundland to central British Columbia, and from Minnesota to Maine, with some populations extending southward into the Appalachian Mountains of West Virginia.

The COBE satellite was dedicated to studying the cosmic microwave background radiation and provided evidence supporting the Big Bang theory. Its work helped shape our understanding of the cosmos and two of its principal investigators received the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2006. The COBE-project is considered the starting point for cosmology as a precision science.
STF is a Michigan prison that houses Level I male inmates.

The William Harvey Hospital, located in Willesborough, Ashford, Kent, England, is one of the three main hospitals in the East Kent Hospitals University NHS Trust area. It is named after William Harvey, a doctor born in Folkestone who discovered the blood circulatory system.
Serkawn Hospital, operated by the Baptist Church of Mizoram, is the first hospital and nursing school in Mizoram, established in 1923 with a registered capacity of 100 beds.

Hare Conditioned is a Looney Tunes cartoon from 1945, directed by Chuck Jones and featuring Bugs Bunny voiced by Mel Blanc. The title is a pun on "air conditioned" and references the use of department stores as a cool escape from hot weather. It was the second Bugs Bunny cartoon in the series.

The 1948 Olympic Games had six events, including the men's team road race cycling event on August 13th. Teams consisted of four riders, and the team's time was calculated by adding the three best finishers.

The men's horizontal bar competition was one of eight events for male competitors in artistic gymnastics at the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney. It took place on September 16 and 25 at the Sydney SuperDome.
WBUS, also known as "93.7 The Bus," is a radio station that plays classic rock music and is licensed to serve Boalsburg, Pennsylvania. It broadcasts to the State College, Pennsylvania area.
The Anglo-Manipur War was a battle between the British Empire and the Kingdom of Manipur that took place from March 31 to April 27, 1891, resulting in a British triumph.

Wrestlepalooza was an annual professional wrestling event held by Extreme Championship Wrestling in Philadelphia in 1995, 1997, 1998, and 2000. The 1998 event was broadcast on pay-per-view and all footage from the four events is owned by WWE.
Belgium's rugby sevens team competes internationally and achieved their highest ranking of sixth place in the Sevens Grand Prix series in 2014.

Lagarde, a family-owned winery in Argentina's Mendoza Province, was founded in 1897 and consists of five vineyards. It is currently managed by the Pescarmona family, with Sofia and Lucila Pescarmona as third-generation owners and Juan Roby Stordeur as winemaker since 2002.
Purple Splendor, also known as Splendor Purple in Europe, is a hybrid cultivar created by Peter Podaras at Hines Nursery in Laguna Hills, CA in 2012.

Founded in 1882 by Rev. A.B. Coit, First Presbyterian Church is a historic congregation in Hattiesburg, Mississippi. It was the town's first church and joined the Presbyterian Church in America in 1973.
Zoologicheskii Zhurnal is a Russian scientific journal that focuses on zoology and was founded by Aleksei Severtsov in 1916.
TJ Štart Nové Zámky is a Slovakian handball team based in Nové Zámky.
The Fluch von Novgorod is a roller coaster located in Hansa-Park, Germany.

UNOSOM II was the second phase of the UN's intervention in Somalia, following UNITAF and UNOSOM I, with the goal of creating a safe environment for humanitarian aid. The intervention is famous for the Battle of Mogadishu, depicted in the book and film Black Hawk Down.

RSUP. Dr. Kariadi is a large and leading hospital in Semarang, Indonesia, affiliated with the Faculty of Medicine Diponegoro University. It is under the responsibility of the General Director of Medical Services, Ministry of Health Republic of Indonesia, and is tasked with organizing medical treatment and rehabilitation efforts in a harmonious, integrated, and sustainable manner.
The MGM Grand Garden Arena in Las Vegas, Nevada hosted UFC 191: Johnson vs. Dodson 2, a mixed martial arts event on September 5, 2015.

The French penal colony of Cayenne, also called Devil's Island, was a well-known prison in the 19th and 20th centuries. It was used for internal exile of French political prisoners, including Captain Alfred Dreyfus, and for deporting criminals from across the French empire. The system was shut down in 1953 due to its harsh treatment of prisoners.
The Black Hills in northwestern San Bernardino County, California are an extension of the Black Hills in Kern County.
The Six Days of Berlin is an annual six-day track cycling race in Berlin, Germany that began in 1909. Klaus Bugdahl has won the most races with nine victories.

WXN82, also known as Valentine All Hazards, is a NOAA Weather Radio station that provides weather and hazard updates for Valentine, Nebraska and nearby areas. It is operated by the National Weather Service in North Platte, Nebraska and broadcasts from a transmitter in Valentine. The station covers Cherry County in Nebraska and Todd and Tripp Counties in South Dakota.
Mtsvane is a white grape variety used in Georgian wine-making, often blended with Rkatsiteli for a fruity and aromatic balance. Its name in Georgian means "new, young, and green."

Atlético Madrid's 2010-11 season was their 105th overall and 74th in La Liga. They aimed for their tenth La Liga title and participated in the UEFA Europa League, starting in the Group stage due to their seventh-place finish in the previous season. They also reached the quarter-finals of the Copa del Rey but were eliminated by Real Madrid, who went on to win the tournament.

Founded in 1983 by three California-based doctors, the Wilderness Medical Society offers support and resources for medical professionals working in remote or outdoor settings. The organization produces publications such as the Wilderness & Environmental Medicine Journal and Practice Guidelines for Wilderness Emergency Care.

The Jerusalem Light Rail is a light rail system in Jerusalem, with the Red Line currently the only one in operation. Construction began in 2002 and ended in 2010, with service beginning in 2011. The line is 13.9 km long with 23 stops, and extensions to the northern suburb of Neve Yaakov and Hadassah Ein Kerem Hospital are currently under construction. The project was criticized for budget overruns and for its route serving Jewish neighborhoods in east Jerusalem. Plans for the Green and Blue lines have been approved.
The Palazzo Baronale is a fortified palace located in Archi, Province of Chieti in Abruzzo, Italy.
Kunkush Kancha is a mountain in the Andes of Peru, reaching a height of 4,600 m. It is located in the Ancash Region, in the Huarmey and Recuay Provinces.

The Dublin Super Cup in 2011 was a two-day football tournament held in Dublin, Ireland at the Aviva Stadium. It included Celtic, F.C. Internazionale, Manchester City, and a League of Ireland XI, with Manchester City ultimately winning.

The Adelphi Canal, located in Duckmanton, England, was a privately owned waterway built in 1799 to transport goods from an ironworks to a nearby wharf. Although it was not connected to any other waterway, goods were transported by road to the Chesterfield Canal.
Josu Larrazabal works as a sports director for the Euskaltel-Euskadi cycling team.

The 2001 FIFA U-17 World Championship was held in Trinidad and Tobago from September 13-30, with players born after January 1, 1984 eligible to participate. France, with two talented players from Le Havre, won the tournament with a 3-0 victory over Nigeria in the final, after winning five of their six games and relying on a 3-5-2 or 3-6-1 formation. Anthony Le Tallec and Florent Sinama-Pongolle were the top scorer and Player of the Tournament, respectively.
The 2004 Armenian Cup was the 13th football competition with 18 participants, including 3 reserve teams.
Teatro Avante is a non-profit theater group situated in Miami, Florida's Little Havana district.
The Seyfert galaxy 3C 452 is situated in the Lacerta constellation.
Aztec: The Curse in the Heart of the City of Gold is a PlayStation adventure game created by Cryo Interactive and released by France Telecom Multimedia on June 1, 2000.

The 1948 Florida Gators football team, coached by Bear Wolf, had a 5-5 overall record and a 1-5 record in the SEC. Notable wins included a 16-9 victory against Auburn and a 27-13 Homecoming win over Miami. They placed tenth out of twelve SEC teams.
Mityana Hospital, also known as Mityana General Hospital or Mityana District Hospital, is located in the town of Mityana in Uganda's Central Region.

In 2012, the Tampa Bay Storm played their 25th season and 21st in Tampa Bay, with Dave Ewart as coach and home games at the Tampa Bay Times Forum. Despite a new logo and uniform colors, they missed the playoffs for the second year in a row with a record of 8-10.
The Tarapoa Airport, also known as Aeropuerto Tarapoa, serves the city of Tarapoa in Ecuador's Sucumbíos province.
VRC-40, also called the "Rawhides", is a US Navy logistics support squadron stationed at NS Norfolk. It was established in 1960 and is one of only two active logistics squadrons in the Navy.

The Dodgeville Municipal Airport, previously known as Governor Dodge Quinn Airport, operated from 1967 to the early 1990s. It was later purchased by a construction firm and renamed Southwind Airport for private use. The only remaining airport in Iowa County is located in Mineral Point, Wisconsin.
TER Centre-Val de Loire is the railway system that operates in the Centre-Val de Loire region of France.
Established in 1905, Ruthin-Pwllglas Golf Club is located in Denbighshire, Wales, just outside Pwllglas. The club features a 9-hole course on parkland and moorland with views of the Clwydian Range.

The Journal of Economic Education (JEE) was established in 1969 as a platform for scholarly work in economic education, primarily at the undergraduate level. The Council for Economic Education oversaw publication until 1981 when it was assigned to Heldref Publications. The JEE became a quarterly publication in 1983 and changed editors several times before being sold to the Taylor & Francis Group in 2009.

The Australian Systematic Botany journal, published by CSIRO, features original research and reviews on topics related to systematic botany, including biogeography, taxonomy, and evolution. It covers all plant, algal, and fungal groups, including fossils, and has been published since 1978 under the name Brunonia before adopting its current name in 1988. Although some members of the editorial team are part of the Australian Systematic Botany Society, the journal is not directly associated with it. Its ISSN is 1030-1887 and it had an impact factor of 1.162 in early 2007.

Sparta Rotterdam played their second season in the Dutch Second League in 2003-2004, after being relegated for the first time in their history in the 2001-2002 season. Mike Snoei took over as manager from Chris Dekker.

Twice-yearly, Northwestern University's not-for-profit literary magazine, TriQuarterly, showcases a variety of genres including fiction, nonfiction, poetry, drama, literary essays, reviews, a blog, and graphic art.
WKVN (95.3 FM) is a radio station in Morganfield, Kentucky that serves the Evansville area and is owned by the Educational Media Foundation. It broadcasts the K-Love network from Rocklin, CA.

The Basej-e Milli, also known as the Afghanistan Green Trend, is a political party founded by Amrullah Saleh, a former Afghan intelligence chief. It began as a grassroots movement promoting democracy and reform while opposing the Taliban. In May 2011, over 20,000 of Saleh's supporters participated in an anti-Taliban protest in Kabul.
Kiełpin, located in the Pomeranian Voivodeship of Poland, is a former railway station of PKP.

Landsat 3, the third satellite of the Landsat program, was launched on March 5, 1978, to provide a global archive of satellite imagery. It was managed solely by NASA and was decommissioned on September 7, 1983, far beyond its expected lifespan of one year.
The discography of Miki Howard includes studio albums, live recordings, compilation albums, music videos, and singles.

The 2014 Indian Women's Football Championship took place from April 27 to May 11 in Dibrugarh and Golaghat, Assam. Twenty states were divided into four groups, with Manipur winning the tournament by defeating Orissa 3-1 in the finals. This was Manipur's 17th championship title.

The Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel, situated at 7000 Hollywood Boulevard in Hollywood, Los Angeles, California, is a historic hotel that has been in operation since May 15, 1927, making it the longest-running hotel in Los Angeles.

The Scottish Junior Football Central District Second Division is part of the West Region of the Scottish Junior Football Association and the top three teams will move up to the Central District First Division.
Sammy Petrillo, an American comedian famous for resembling Jerry Lewis, was a nightclub and movie performer.

The Hammersmith & City line of the London Underground runs between Hammersmith and Barking, serving 29 stations in 15.8 miles. It runs below ground in the central section between Paddington and Bow Road and skirts the City of London between Farringdon and Aldgate East. The line was opened in 1863 and was electrified in 1906. It is being upgraded to increase capacity by 65% by 2019.

York City Football Club won the 1983-84 Football League Fourth Division, becoming the first club to reach 100 points in a season. They also entered the FA Cup, League Cup, and Associate Members' Cup, but were knocked out in the early rounds. John MacPhail, Gary Ford, and John Byrne played in all 52 first-team matches, with Byrne scoring 28 goals and MacPhail winning the Clubman of the Year award.
The Mukacheve Diocese is a part of the Catholic Church in Ukraine, led by Bishop Antal Majnek since 1997.
Gulf Commercial Bank is an Iraqi commercial bank based in Baghdad with 12 branches in various cities.

The Front Royal-Warren County Airport is a publicly owned airport located 3 nautical miles west of Front Royal, Virginia. It is classified as a general aviation facility and is part of the National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems.
Fiesta Mall is a shopping center in Mesa, Arizona, situated between Southern Avenue and the US 60 freeway, west of Alma School Road. It is part of the Phoenix metropolitan area.
C. donfaustoi, also called the eastern Santa Cruz tortoise, is a type of Galápagos tortoise found on Santa Cruz Island. It was previously considered a part of C. porteri until 2015.
The biggest mall in Chennai, Tamil Nadu, India is Phoenix Market City, which was developed by Phoenix Mills Limited and opened in January 2013.

Shōnen Star, the Indonesian version of Weekly Shōnen Sunday, was published by Elex Media Komputindo in 2005. The magazine featured titles such as Kurozakuro, Robot Boys, My Wing, and Midori's Days. However, due to strict censorship regulations, the magazine's publication frequency was increased from monthly to twice a month in July 2010. The magazine was ultimately cancelled in November 2013 at volume 16.
Kyle Hotz is a comic book writer and artist from the United States who has contributed to Marvel Comics, DC Comics, Image Comics, and Dark Horse Comics.
The 2005 Copa Nissan Sudamericana de Clubes was a football competition for CONMEBOL clubs, with invited teams from CONCACAF. Boca Juniors won the tournament for the second time.

Lux Occulta is a Polish avant-garde metal band that was established in 1994. Their music is influenced by progressive and black metal, and often includes complex arrangements with multiple sections and unexpected time changes.

The Marwar Junction-Munabao railway line connects two stations in Rajasthan, India, with a link to Jodhpur, and is managed by the North Western Railway. Munabao is the final station in India before the India-Pakistan border.

The Louisiana Museum of Natural History is located on the Louisiana State University campus in Baton Rouge and includes the LSU Museum of Natural Science, the LSU Herbarium, the Louisiana State Arthropod Museum, and the Textile and Costume Museum. The Natural Science branch has collections of mineralogy, petrology, and palynology, as well as Louisiana Geological Survey data repositories.
The ULB Düsseldorf is a central service institution of Heinrich Heine University and one of the three State Libraries of North Rhine-Westphalia, along with Bonn and Münster.
Don Wilkerson's first album, The Texas Twister, was recorded in 1960 and released on the Riverside label.

The Hill Stakes is a Group 2 horse race held in September at Randwick Racecourse in Sydney, Australia. The race is run over a distance of 2000 metres at Weight for Age and offers a total prize money of A$200,000.
The FA Trophy's 25th season was in 1993-94.

İstanbul BŞB is a professional basketball team from Turkey that competes in the Turkish Basketball Super League and plays at Cebeci Sport Hall. It is a part of İstanbul Büyükşehir Belediyesi Sports Club.

George Tod, a British surveyor and hothouse builder, published a book in 1807 that included illustrations and descriptions of 26 glass houses, mostly of his own design, built for various noblemen and gentlemen in England. The book provides plans, elevations, and sections of hothouses, greenhouses, conservatories, and an aquarium. The book was well-received and priced at £2. 12s. 6d. in a review in The Literary Panorama.
The Polish Institute of Arts and Sciences of America publishes the quarterly English-language academic journal, the Polish Review, which was founded in 1956 and is based in New York City.
Every year, Harold Park in Sydney hosts the New South Wales Derby, a traditional harness racing event for three-year-old horses.
The Prix Kergorlay is a flat horse race for thoroughbreds aged three or older in France, held annually in August at Deauville over a distance of 3,000 metres.
Betty Boop stars in the 1934 Fleischer Studios animated short film, Betty in Blunderland, which is included in 50 Classic Cartoons Volume 3.

The Pharping Hydro Power Project, located in the Kathmandu district, is Nepal's first and Asia's second hydro-power project. It was declared a Living Museum by the Nepalese government in 2010 and is now open to the public.

The following is a list of Dalida's songs recorded and/or performed between 1954 and 1987, and posthumously between 1987 and 2014. The list includes over 1000 songs, organized alphabetically by language and chronologically by recording, performance, and/or release.
Ariel Rivera's fifth album, "Getting to Know," achieved platinum status due to its success.
NGC 3059, a faint, large, and irregularly round barred spiral galaxy, was discovered by John Herschel on February 22, 1835 in the Carina constellation.

From 1933 to 1945, the Gauliga Württemberg was the top football league in the German state of Württemberg and the Prussian province of Hohenzollern. The league was formed before the Nazis reorganised the administrative regions in Germany, and the Gau Württemberg-Hohenzollern replaced the Prussian province and state of Württemberg.
Casse dell'Umbria is an Italian retail bank located in Terni, Umbria and is a subsidiary of Intesa Sanpaolo. Its headquarters is situated near Fondazione Carit on Corso Tacito in Terni.
Jordan Lane Price plays the role of Celia Fitzgerald, a fictional character in the revived version of the soap opera All My Children, which premiered on April 29, 2013.

The Paso de los Libres-Uruguaiana International Bridge spans the Uruguay River, connecting Argentina and Brazil via a 1,419-meter road and railroad bridge between Paso de los Libres, Corrientes Province, Argentina, and Uruguaiana, Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil.

Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball team played in the 1929-30 NCAA Division I college basketball season, coached by Bill Dudack. They were independent and played their home games at Tech Gymnasium and Brookland Gymnasium in Washington, D.C.

Project.R is a Japanese musical group formed by Nippon Columbia and Toei Company to create soundtracks for the Super Sentai Series. The group consists of various popular anime vocalists who perform opening and ending themes and insert songs for the series. Some songs are performed by non-members, but composed by Project.R members.

The 2003-04 Arab Champions League was the inaugural edition of a new format that replaced the Arab Champions Cup and Prince Faysal bin Fahad Tournament for Arab Clubs. It featured teams from Arab nations in Africa and Asia, with CS Sfaxien of Tunisia emerging as the champions after defeating El-Ismaily of Egypt in the final.

Alashkert Stadium is a football stadium in Yerevan, Armenia, previously known as Nairi Stadium. It was built in 1960 and has a capacity of 6,850 spectators. It is the home ground of Alashkert FC and is located in the Shengavit district adjacent to Lake Yerevan. The stadium was renamed by new owners in 2013 and will be renovated and possibly expanded to a capacity of 10,000 by 2015.

The Battle of Pensacola was fought between Confederate troops in Pensacola Bay and the Union fleet led by Harvey Brown. Despite a lengthy siege, the Confederates maintained control of the city and its forts.

The Goodwood is a Group 1 Thoroughbred horse race held at Morphettville Racecourse in Adelaide, Australia during the SAJC Autumn Carnival, covering a distance of 1200 metres and run with set weights and penalties. It should not be confused with the American horse race called the Goodwood Handicap, which is also known as the Goodwood Stakes.
U.C.C. or Assigeco Casalpusterlengo is an Italian basketball team located in Codogno, Lombardy.

Dean Park, located in Bournemouth, England, is a cricket ground that is currently utilized by Dorset County Cricket Club, Bournemouth University Cricket Club, Parley Cricket Club, and Suttoners Cricket Club. It was previously used by Hampshire County Cricket Club.

The local cup and championship oversee two divisions in the men's category during the 2011-12 season: a premier division with 10 clubs and a second division with 3 clubs. The winner of the first division enters the playoffs and has a chance to move up to the Fourth Division, while the last-place team is relegated.

Lee Wong founded Alt Variety, a monthly publication based in New York City that focused on alternative and subversive topics. It began as an online publication in February 2012 and ceased operations in July 2013.

KZZ64, also known as Ekron All Hazards, is a NOAA Weather Radio station that provides weather and hazard information for Ekron, Kentucky and nearby cities. It covers several counties in Kentucky and Indiana and is programmed from the National Weather Service forecast office in Louisville, Kentucky.

Ishihara is a main belt asteroid that was discovered on April 16, 1993 by K. Endate and K. Watanabe. It orbits the Sun every 3.22 years and was named after Takahiro Ishihara, a former president of the Hiroshima Astronomical Society.
Hurricane Chris, an American rapper, has released two studio albums, one independent album, six mixtapes, six music videos, and six singles (including two as a featured artist).
Theresetta Catholic School, located in Castor, Alberta, Canada, is a Catholic school named after its patron saint, Saint Thérèse, and led by Principal Roger Fetaz.
Hero Sharqi is a locality in Taunsa Tehsil, Dera Ghazi Khan District, Punjab, Pakistan.

The SRSC at Algoma University is an archive and education center that collects and preserves materials related to residential schools, healing, reconciliation, and Indigenous communities. It is governed by Algoma University and the Children of Shingwauk Alumni Association and partners with the Engracia de Jesus Matias Archives and Special Collections.

New Plymouth's public transport is experiencing a resurgence after years of little council support. The system now covers the city and surrounding areas, with new routes and increased service levels introduced in 2010. The expanded service was initially funded on a trial basis for two years and became permanent in 2012.

Tanzania Democratic Alliance (TADEA) is a political party in Tanzania, registered on August 28, 1992, and currently led by John D. Lifa Chipaka. It is scheduled to hold its Annual Conference on June 29-30, 2014, in Dar-es-salaam.

The following is a record of Swedish football transfers during the summer transfer window of 2013, categorized by club. It only includes transfers that occurred between July 15th and August 11th, 2013, within the Allsvenskan and Superettan leagues.
At the 1976 Summer Olympics, the women's team foil was one of eight fencing events and had 61 fencers from 13 nations competing from July 27 to 28. It was the fifth time the event had been held.

The Novgorod and Staraya Russa Diocese is a historic office in the Russian Orthodox Church, with medieval archbishops who played important roles in Russian history and culture. They supported the construction of churches and influenced Russian art and architecture, as well as chronicle-writing.

The Basque conflict was a political and armed conflict between Spain and the Basque National Liberation Movement, which sought independence from Spain and France. The conflict was primarily fought on Spanish soil, with ETA being the main separatist organization. The conflict resulted in the deaths of over 1,000 people, including civilians, politicians, and security officers. ETA announced a "definitive cessation of its armed activity" in 2011.
Two regional airlines operate feeder flights for Air New Zealand under the brand name Air New Zealand Link, connecting regional centres with the country's three main international airports.

The Glass Bottle, a pop band led by Gary Criss, had a hit with "I Ain't Got Time Anymore" in 1971, produced by Dickie Goodman who formed the band to promote the glass industry. The band had two hits before disbanding, and Gary Criss had solo success in the disco era. Their song "Wonderwheel" was in the film "The People Next Door". Cliff Richard had a UK hit with his version of "I Ain't Got Time Anymore" in 1970.
Fenerbahçe has been in the Süper Lig for 57 years in a row and has existed for 107 years.
Intelsat 27, an American communications satellite meant to replace Intelsat 805, was destroyed when the rocket carrying it crashed into the Pacific Ocean 56 seconds after launch.

The Delta Discovery is a weekly newspaper that covers Bethel, Alaska, and the surrounding villages in the Yukon-Kuskokwim Delta and Bristol Bay regions of southwestern Alaska. Its slogan, "Real news for the real people," reflects the indigenous name of the local tribe.
